To prove the target statement:
> For any `I J : Set α`, if `J` is matchable in `G` and `I ⊆ J`, then `I` is matchable in `G`,

we proceed as follows:

1. Since `J` is matchable in `G`, there exists a matching `M` of `G` such that `J ⊆ V(G, M)`.
2. Since `I ⊆ J`, it follows that `I ⊆ V(G, M)`.
3. The same matching `M` then works to show that `I` is matchable in `G`.

The key observation is that if `J` is a subset of the vertex set of some matching `M`, then any subset `I` of `J` is also a subset of the vertex set of `M`, so `M` is also a witness that `I` is matchable.

